  "text": "Kent et al. proposed to let ISPs extract only necessary information from certificates and AAs, and push the data to their routers [CITATION_1] . Routers do not need to store signatures for certificates and AAs. Such optimization may save 50%-60% of the corresponding memory. We adjust the above calculation accordingly. The resulting overall memory saving is estimated as 67%. Moreover, if we consider the extracted information from certificates, the space impacts of different signature algorithms come from their key sizes. Shown in Table 3 , the 1024-bit DSA with 160-bit exponent requires about 408 bytes to store the public key and domain parameters. This number is higher than the key size for BLS or RSA, which suggests that we can expect the overall memory saving to be slightly higher than 67%.",
